A Party Peel (aka Lunch Peel) is a gentle, quick chemical peel that gives you instant glow with zero downtime. Ideal before events, it’s safe, effective, and you can return to work or makeup immediately.

How it Works:

Uses mild AHAs/BHAs (like glycolic, lactic, or salicylic acid)
Gently exfoliates dead skin
Brightens dull skin
Refines pores & texture
Improves makeup finish

 Quick Facts:

Time: 15–30 minutes
Glow: Visible in 24 hours
Downtime: None
Best For: Dull skin, event prep, bridal glow

I was once just a little girl with big dreams and no clear path ahead. I didn’t know how things would turn out, and there were many moments when I felt tired, confused, and unsure if I could really do it. But step by step, day by day, I kept learning, growing, and believing in myself.

Becoming a dermatologist wasn’t easy. It took hard work, patience, and a lot of quiet determination. There were late nights studying, challenges to overcome, and times when I doubted my own strength. But I never gave up because deep down I knew this was what I was meant to do.

Today, I’m thankful to be able to help others through my work and do something I truly love. This journey has taught me that success doesn’t happen overnight and every small effort counts.

My story is a simple one. Just a reminder that no matter where you start, with patience and faith, you can reach your dreams. Every expert was once a beginner, and every journey begins with one small step.

Should I try Korean skincare?

If you’ve asked yourself this after scrolling through Instagram or watching K-drama routines, you’re not alone. But let’s break it down not as a trend, but as a skin investment.

As a dermatologist, I get this question almost every single day. And here’s what most people don’t know:

Korean skincare was originally formulated for cool, dry climates. The layers of hydrating serums, essences, ampoules, and sleeping masks? They’re designed to trap moisture in an environment where your skin tends to lose it.

But in Indian weather where it’s hot, humid, and dusty those same layers can clog your pores, lead to breakouts, and disturb your natural oil balance.
Especially if you already have oily, acne-prone, or combination skin (which many of us do!), this can make things worse.

Now, does that mean all Korean skincare is bad for Indian skin?
❌ No.

✅ It depends on the formulation, your skin type, and the climate you live in.
For example, if you have very dry skin, or you’re constantly in an air-conditioned environment, some Korean products might help  if chosen wisely.

But blindly following a 10-step K-beauty routine because it’s trending? That’s where things go wrong.

Our skin is built differently. Our environment is different. Our lifestyles are different.
So our skincare should be too.

👉 Before investing in pretty packaging and glowing promises, always check the ingredients, listen to your skin, and if you can consult a dermatologist.

Skincare is not one-size-fits-all. Your skin deserves better than just following a trend.

Stress can significantly affect your skin in multiple ways, both directly and indirectly. Here’s how:

1. Triggers Hormonal Imbalance
When you’re stressed, your body releases cortisol (the stress hormone). High cortisol levels:

Increase oil production in the skin, leading to clogged pores and acne breakouts
Disrupt other hormones, worsening PCOD-related skin issues like facial hair and pigmentation.

2. Weakens Skin Barrier
Stress weakens the skin’s protective barrier, which can lead to:
Dryness
Flakiness
Sensitivity or redness
Increased risk of infections and eczema.

3. Slows Down Healing
Stress impairs your skin’s ability to repair itself, so:

Wounds, pimples, and rashes take longer to heal
Inflammatory conditions like psoriasis or rosacea may worsen.

4. Aggravates Pre-existing Conditions
Stress can trigger or worsen:
Psoriasis
Eczema
Rosacea
Hives and allergic flare-ups

5. Accelerates Aging
Chronic stress increases free radical activity and decreases collagen production, leading to:
Fine lines
Wrinkles
Dullness
Sagging skin

6. Lifestyle Changes from Stress
Stress often leads to:
Poor sleep (affects skin repair)
Junk food cravings (causing breakouts)
Skipping skincare routines (dullness and dryness)

How to Protect Your Skin During Stress
Stick to a basic skincare routine: 

gentle cleanser, moisturizer, SPF
Hydrate well
Prioritize sleep and relaxation
Practice breathing, yoga, or journaling
Eat anti-inflammatory foods: berries, greens, turmeric, nuts

No matter how expensive your serums or facials are, if you skip sunscreen, you’re undoing all the good work.

Here’s your complete guide to sunscreen:

1. How to choose the right sunscreen:

SPF 30 to 50 is perfect for daily use
Must have broad-spectrum protection (UVA + UVB)
Look for PA+++ or higher for deeper protection
Gel-based or matte for oily/acne-prone skin
Cream-based or hydrating for dry/sensitive skin
Water-resistant if you sweat or swim.

2. Application Rules:

Use the 2-finger rule for face & neck
Apply 20 mins before sun exposure
Reapply every 3-4 hours if you’re outdoors
Don’t skip ears, neck, arms, hands, and even your feet!

3. What about sunscreen powder?

It’s a game-changer for reapplication!
Works great over makeup or if you’re out and can’t use cream
Look for tinted mineral sunscreen powders with SPF 30+

Bonus tip: Blue light from your screens can also age your skin so don’t skip sunscreen indoors either.
